ce:section.ce:para:
In this regard, a reduced graphene oxide-multiwalled carbon nanotubes (rGO-MWCNTs)/chitosan/CQD aptasensing platform has been reported by Rezaei and co-workers for selective electrochemical detection of Lyz [99]. Nano graphene composites have highlighted owing to the great electron motility, contribute synergetic of functional moieties, great surface area and other benefits [100,101]. Furthermore, MWCNTs as other type of NPs, can be utilized as a moderator in the electrochemical aptasensing platforms [102–104], because of their good conductance and high surface areas [105], for better immobilizing of Apts. Moreover, CQDs have very favorable characteristics in developing of aptasensors [106]. Hence, in this study, a glass carbon electrode modification was constructed with a nanocomposite consisted of rGO-MWCNTs/chitosan/CQDs. This nano surface prepares a proper platform for better immobilizing of Apts owing to the presence of several carboxyl, hydroxyl and amino moieties in rGO-MWCNTs and CQD. Moreover, the nanocomposite helps to progressing sensitivity and leads to significant increment of the electrochemical signal. The amino-bounded Lyz Apts were able to link on the surface of nano platform via chemical interaction between the NH2 groups of the nanocomposite and the NH2 groups of the Apts by applying glutaraldehyde as a linker. Briefly, when the Lyz was added to the system, the above-mentioned Apt selectively captured the Lyz on the electrode surface that causes an enhancement in Charge Transfer Resistance (R

                           ct
                        ) in electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) as an analytical signal and a reduction in the differential pulse voltammetry (DPV) peak current (Fig. 1
                        ). This aptasensor detected Lyz in wide detection ranges (10 fM to 100 nM and 20 fM to 10 nM) with very low limit of detections (LODs) of 1.9 and 3.7 fM for EIS and DPV respectively.
